Abbot Walter of St Edmund’s twice entertained king Henry Ill, and on one occasion the abbcy was distinguished by the presence of queen Eleanor arrd the young prince Edward. A few years afterwards king Henry honoured the abbey by selecting abbot John de Oaux for his treasurer. Abbot John was a relative of queen Elcanor. Mr. Foss, with his accustomed accuracy‚ gives proof of his acting as ajustice itinerant from 1254 to 1258.ι He died in 1263, and was succeeded by Robert de Sutton, a good, weak man, called to the government in times which required more than ordinary energy and decision. The country was torn by internal dissention. The abbot gave shelter and encouragement to both parties.
